<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFE7FFCBFF04EBB4FE93FDEF" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF04EBB4FE93FDEF" blockId="18.[178,1086,417,586]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
Comment: 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFEDEEBB4FDA6FE11" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1931" box="[360,590,417,439]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFEDEEBB4FDA6FE11" box="[360,590,417,439]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">Scymbalium nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described as a &quot;variety&quot; of 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFB9CEBB7FE2AFE72" authority="EPPELSHEIM. The" authorityName="EPPELSHEIM. The" authorityYear="1890" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicum">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFB9CEBB7FEEBFE72" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">S. indicum</emphasis>
EPPELSHEIM. The
</taxonomicName>
description is based on an unspecified number of 
<typeStatus id="4E66882AFFE7FFCBFC52EBAAFBD5FE72" box="[996,1085,447,468]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">syntypes</typeStatus>
from &quot;Calcutta&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="F54C4B79FFE7FFCBFED1EBC9FDE7FE54" author="CAMERON M" box="[359,527,476,498]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" refId="ref22842" refString="CAMERON M (1931) The Fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma. Coleoptera. Staphylinidae. Volume 2. - London, Taylor and Francis: viii + 257 pp." type="book" year="1931">CAMERON 1931</bibRefCitation>
). Six partly incomplete 
<typeStatus id="4E66882AFFE7FFCBFCB9EBC9FC80FE57" box="[783,872,476,497]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">syntypes</typeStatus>
were located in the Cameron collection at the BMNH. A male is designated as the 
<typeStatus id="4E66882AFFE7FFCBFC87EBECFC79FDA9" box="[817,913,505,527]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">lectotype</typeStatus>
. An examination of the type material revealed that 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFDBFE802FD69FD8A" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1931" box="[521,641,535,556]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFDBFE802FD69FD8A" box="[521,641,535,556]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">S. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a distinct species and belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFEAFE821FE9EFDEC" box="[281,374,564,586]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFEAFE821FE9EFDEC" box="[281,374,564,586]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">Micrillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFE7FFCBFF04E84CFF1BFCB7" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" type="description">
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF04E84CFBFBFD2A" blockId="18.[178,1086,601,652]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
Redescription: Body length 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFE7FFCBFDE5E84CFD3AFDC9" box="[595,722,601,623]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.5">4.5-5.5 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFE7FFCBFC0DE84CFBD2FDC9" box="[955,1082,601,623]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="2.7" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" unit="mm" value="2.8" valueMax="2.9" valueMin="2.7">2.7-2.9 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: body including appendages pale reddish, with the head somewhat darker.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF04E88EFD41FD17" blockId="18.[178,681,667,689]" box="[178,681,667,689]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
External characters similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFD8FE889FD4BFD17" baseAuthorityName="Eppelsheim" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[569,675,667,689]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFD8FE889FD4BFD17" box="[569,675,667,689]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF71E8D4FF1BFCB7" blockId="18.[178,1086,705,785]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
: sternite VIII distinctly oblong, posterior excision narrow and rather deep (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFE7FFCBFC54E8D4FBD9FD71" box="[994,1073,705,727]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFE7FFCBFEABE8CBFE64FD52" box="[285,396,734,756]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">Figs 15-16</figureCitation>
) very small, 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFE7FFCBFDA5E8CBFD86FD52" box="[531,622,734,756]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" unit="mm" value="0.35">0.35 mm</quantity>
long, strongly asymmetric, and of distinctive shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFE7FFCBFF04E935FE3BFC0A" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF04E935FE3BFC0A" blockId="18.[178,1086,800,940]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
Comparative notes: The similar external and male sexual characters suggest that 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFEA7E92AFE7AFCF2" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1931" box="[273,402,831,852]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scymbalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFEA7E92AFE7AFCF2" box="[273,402,831,852]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFE7FFCBFDDDE92AFD30FCF2" baseAuthorityName="Eppelsheim" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[619,728,830,852]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFE7FFCBFDDDE92AFD30FCF2" box="[619,728,830,852]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it is distinguished by the darker head, the shape of the male sternite VIII (slightly more oblong), and the slightly different shape of the smaller aedeagus (apex of ventral process shorter, internal structure of different shape).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFE7FFCBFF04E9AEFEE3FC48" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="91623688FFE7FFCBFF04E9AEFEE3FC48" blockId="18.[178,1085,955,1006]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">
Distribution: This species is currently known only from northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="E9CA7618FFE7FFCBFBBFE9AEFBD5FC77" box="[1033,1085,955,977]" name="India" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFE7FFCBFF0FE9CDFF15FC48" box="[185,253,984,1006]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="17.[178,223,1423,1443]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,552,1406]" captionTargetId="figure-217@17.[178,1085,552,1406]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Map 3: Distributions of Micrillus indicus (EPPELSHEIM) (triangles), M. nigriceps (CAMERON) (diamonds), M. intermedius (CAMERON) (open and filled circles), and M. siamensis nov.sp. (filled circle) in the Oriental region, based on examined records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6512094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6512094/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1497">Map 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
